    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Colors commonly associated with fire, such as reds, oranges, and yellows, which suggest warmth and which appear to advance. The optical tendency for warm colors to advance before cool colors had been long exploited by European and Oriental painters as a method of suggesting spatial depth.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000000051/Pierce, From Abacus to Zeus (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Colores comúnmente asociados con fuego, tales como rojos, naranjas y amarillos, que sugieres calidez y que parecen avanzar.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Kleuren die vaak worden geassocieerd met vuur, bijvoorbeeld kleurschakeringen van rood, oranje en geel, die een warme indruk geven en zich naar de voorgrond lijken te dringen. Het optische verschijnsel waarbij warme kleuren meer op de voorgrond lijken te treden dan koele kleuren, wordt van oudsher door Europese en oosterse schilders benut om een ruimtelijk effect en diepte te suggereren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099099/Van Dale groot woordenboek (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>暖色通常讓人聯想到火焰，如紅色、橙色與黃色。帶有溫暖的感覺，看起來有前進的視覺效果。利用暖色相對於冷色有前進視覺效果的特質，長久以來，歐洲和東方畫家已發展出一套營造視覺空間深度的技法。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cores comumente associadas ao fogo, como vermelho, laranja e amarelo, que sugerem calor e que parecem avançar. A tendência óptica de cores quentes avançarem antes das cores frias foi explorada por muito tempo por pintores europeus e orientais como um método de sugerir profundidade espacial.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
